</table>
<p><b>Kim Stanley Robinson</b> (born <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1952-03-23"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="03-23"><a href="/wiki/March_23" title="March 23">March 23</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1952" title="1952">1952</a></span>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction" title="Science fiction">science fiction</a> <a href="/wiki/Writer" title="Writer">writer</a>, probably best known for his award-winning <a href="/wiki/Mars_trilogy" title="Mars trilogy">Mars trilogy</a>.</p>
<p>His work delves into <a href="/wiki/Ecological" title="Ecological" class="mw-redirect">ecological</a> and <a href="/wiki/Sociological" title="Sociological" class="mw-redirect">sociological</a> themes regularly, and many of his novels appear to be the direct result of his own scientific fascinations, such as the 15 years of research and lifelong fascination with <a href="/wiki/Mars" title="Mars">Mars</a> which culminated in his most famous work. He has, due to his fascination with Mars, become a member of the <a href="/wiki/Mars_Society" title="Mars Society">Mars Society</a>.</p>
<p>Robinson's work has been labeled by reviewers as "literary science fiction".<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Robinson will be an instructor at the <a href="/wiki/Clarion_Workshop" title="Clarion Workshop">Clarion Workshop</a> in 2009. In 2010, Robinson will be Guest of Honor at the 68th <a href="/wiki/Worldcon" title="Worldcon">World Science Fiction Convention</a> to be held in Melbourne, Australia.</p>
